{
  "doc_id": "57520",
  "text": "Recently, in some studies, metabolic factors were shown to be associated with an increased prevalence of colorectal tumors. Limburg et al. and Elwing et al. demonstrated the association between diabetes mellitus and colorectal tumors [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Otani et al. and Liu et al. showed a relationship between dyslipidemia and colorectal tumors [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Kim et al. and Orranapalai et al. proved that metabolic syndrome was associated with colorectal tumors [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . The incidence rates of metabolic factors have dramatically increased in developed countries as a result of the high prevalence of obesity [CITATION_7] . Therefore, metabolic factors rank as important risk factors for the increase of prevalence of colorectal tumors. Metabolic factors have also been suggested as risk factors for recurrence after endoscopic removal of colorectal adenomas. To the best of our knowledge, however, no study as yet has discussed whether the presence of metabolic factors might accelerate the development of recurrence after endoscopic removal of colorectal adenomas.",
